{
  "doc_id": "55395",
  "text": "The finding that RSV was the major etiology in young children with ARIs under 5 years were consistent with studies from china and other countries, 6,7,16,22-26 and indicated that prevention strategies for RSV such immunization when a suitable vaccine is available in the future could have large public health impact in Gansu province. HRV, the etiology with highest detection rate in adults, was supported by previous studies that revealed common cold were mainly caused by HRV infections for adults people. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] In addition, Flu was an important virus identified in older children and elderly, which suggested influenza virus was the significant cause of ARIs for those population in relatively undeveloped region of china like Gansu province. Influenza vaccine was commercially available, such as inactivated vaccine, which was administered intramuscularly or intranasally. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] However, it had an extremely low coverage rate in China. [CITATION_6] We considered Influenza vaccine should be used in widespread areas to reduce the incidence of influenza disease in Gansu. It should be noted that PIV was a another major virus for children aged 1-5 years besides RSV, which was in agreement with studies conducted before. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] This finding indicated that local pediatricians not only took priority over RSV infections but also paid more attention to PIV, when younger children were infected with respiratory viruses.",
